# Flipper — Bayesian Fault Probability Architecture

## Vision

Move fault detection from pure LLM inference to a hybrid system where AI is guided by statistically grounded fault probabilities. The model gets smarter with every listing processed, informed by both UK government MOT failure data and our own accumulating observations.

---

## The Problem with Pure LLM Detection

Today the AI detects faults from a blank slate for every listing. It has no memory of what it has seen before and no statistical grounding in what actually goes wrong on specific vehicles. A 2007 VW Golf at 120k miles has well-known failure patterns — the AI shouldn't have to infer these from scratch every time.

---

## Architecture Overview

Three layers working together:

```
Layer 1 — Prior Knowledge      mot_failure_priors
           (DVSA MOT data)     Millions of verified real-world fault rates
                                    ↓
Layer 2 — Observed Outcomes    listing_fault_outcomes  
           (our pipeline)      Every fault we detect, accumulating daily
                                    ↓
Layer 3 — Computed Posteriors  fault_probability_cache
           (nightly job)       Bayesian update combining layers 1 + 2
                                    ↓
           Used by             Detection worker Step 3 — informed priors fed to AI
                               Scoring worker — probability-weighted risk scores
```

