## Fault Type Normalisation (Critical)

The Bayesian model only works if fault types are consistent. `brake_calipers_rear`, `rear_brake_caliper`, and `caliper_rear` are the same fault but would be treated as three separate data points.

### Normalisation rules:
- Always `snake_case`
- Always noun-first: `brake_calipers_rear` not `rear_brake_calipers`
- No spaces, no hyphens
- Standard vocabulary enforced at write time — map non-standard strings to canonical equivalents before inserting into `detected_faults` or `listing_fault_outcomes`

### Canonical fault vocabulary (seed list — grows over time):
```
engine:       timing_chain_failure | engine_failure | head_gasket_failure | 
              turbocharger_failure | injector_failure | oil_leak | coolant_leak

transmission: clutch_failure | gearbox_failure | dsg_failure

brakes:       brake_calipers_rear | brake_calipers_front | brake_discs_worn |
              handbrake_cable | abs_failure | handbrake_control_module

steering:     power_steering_failure | steering_rack_failure | 
              power_steering_pump_failure

electrical:   battery_aged | alternator_failure | starter_motor_failure |
              ecu_failure | immobiliser_failure | abs_sensor_failure

suspension:   shock_absorber_failure | wheel_bearing_failure | 
              control_arm_failure | anti_roll_bar_link

body/misc:    no_mot | lighting_rear_number_plate | windscreen_damage |
              catalytic_converter_failure
```

